{"cursor":"7321","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":A hillock is also a small [[hill]]. {{Infobox Anatomy | Name = | Latin =\nColliculus axonis | GraySubject = | GrayPage = | Image = Axon Hillock.png |\nCaption = red labeled is pointing directly at the axon hillock. | Image2 = |\nCaption2 = | Precursor = | System = | Artery = | Vein = | Nerve = | Lymph = |\nMeshName = | MeshNumber = | Code = | }} The 'axon hillock' is a specialized part\nof the cell body (or soma) of a neuron that connects to the axon. As a result,\nthe axon hillock is the last site in the soma where membrane potentials\npropagated from synaptic inputs are summated before being transmitted to the\naxon. For many years, it had been believed that the axon hillock was the usual\nsite of action potential initiation. It is now thought that the earliest site of\naction potential initiation is found just adjacent, in the initial\n(unmyelinated) segment of the axon. {{cite journal\n| doi = 10.1177/1073858409341973 author = Clark BD, Goldberg EM, and Rudy B\n| title = Electrogenic Tuning of the Axon Initial Segment journal =\n| Neuroscientist volume = 15 issue = 6 pages = 651â668 pmid = 20007821 url =\n| http://nro.sagepub.com/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=20007821 accessdate = 2010-05-\n| 02 date = December, 2009 pmc = 2951114}} However, the positive point, at\n| which the action potential starts, varies between cells. It can also be\n| altered by hormonal stimulation of the neuron, or by second messenger effects\n| of neurotransmitters. The axon hillock also functions as a tight junction,\n| since it acts as a barrier for lateral diffusion of transmembrane proteins,\n| GPI anchored proteins such as thy1, and lipids embedded in the plasma\n| membrane.\n","linknr":355,"url":"axon_hillock","recorded":1376415568,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Axon_hillock&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Axon_hillock&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikip